---
import PageShell from '../../components/PageShell.astro';
import CTABox from '../../components/CTABox.astro';
import ComparisonTable from '../../components/ComparisonTable.astro';

const tocItems = [
  { id: 'top-picks', text: 'Our Top Picks', level: 2 },
  { id: 'leaving-india', text: 'Leaving Indian Healthcare', level: 2 },
  { id: 'destination-considerations', text: 'Destination Considerations', level: 2 },
  { id: 'comparison-table', text: 'Quick Comparison', level: 2 },
  { id: 'detailed-reviews', text: 'Detailed Reviews', level: 2 },
  { id: 'popular-destinations', text: 'Popular Destinations', level: 2 },
  { id: 'faqs', text: 'Common Questions', level: 2 },
];

const relatedLinks = [
  { title: 'Cigna Global Review', href: '/providers/cigna-global' },
  { title: 'Bupa Global Review', href: '/providers/bupa-global' },
  { title: 'Best US Coverage Insurance', href: '/best/us-coverage-insurance' },
  { title: 'Best UK Expat Insurance', href: '/best/uk-expat-insurance' },
  { title: 'Best Gulf Region Insurance', href: '/best/gulf-region-insurance' },
];

const comparisonColumns = [
  { key: 'provider', header: 'Provider' },
  { key: 'usNetwork', header: 'US Network' },
  { key: 'gulfNetwork', header: 'Gulf Network' },
  { key: 'indiaCoverage', header: 'India Coverage' },
  { key: 'price', header: 'Starting Price' },
];

const comparisonRows = [
  { provider: 'Cigna Global', usNetwork: 'Strong', gulfNetwork: 'Strong', indiaCoverage: 'Add-on', price: '$180/mo' },
  { provider: 'Bupa Global', usNetwork: 'Excellent', gulfNetwork: 'Excellent', indiaCoverage: 'Add-on', price: '$200/mo' },
  { provider: 'Allianz Care', usNetwork: 'Good', gulfNetwork: 'Strong', indiaCoverage: 'Add-on', price: '$175/mo' },
  { provider: 'Now Health', usNetwork: 'Good', gulfNetwork: 'Excellent', indiaCoverage: 'Included', price: '$160/mo' },
  { provider: 'ICICI Lombard', usNetwork: 'Limited', gulfNetwork: 'Good', indiaCoverage: 'Included', price: '$120/mo' },
];
---

<PageShell
  title="Best Health Insurance for Indian Expats 2026"
  description="Compare international health insurance for Indian expats. Find coverage for the US, UK, Gulf countries, and other destinations."
  headline="Best Insurance for Indian Expats in 2026"
  subheadline="India's diaspora spans the globe—from Silicon Valley to the Gulf states. Here's how to stay protected wherever your career takes you."
  heroBackgroundImage="/images/pages/indian-expat-hero-bg.png"
  tocItems={tocItems}
  relatedLinks={relatedLinks}
  ctaButtonText="Get Cigna Quote →"
  ctaButtonHref="/go/cigna-global"
>
  <h2 id="top-picks">Our Top Picks</h2>
  <p>
    Indian expats are found in significant numbers in the US, UK, UAE, Saudi Arabia, Canada, and Australia. Healthcare costs vary dramatically by destination—the US and Gulf countries require comprehensive coverage. Here's what we recommend:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Cigna Global:</strong> Best overall for Indian expats. Strong networks in the US and Gulf, comprehensive coverage, reliable service.</li>
    <li><strong>Bupa Global:</strong> Premium option with excellent worldwide networks. Top-tier service quality.</li>
    <li><strong>Now Health:</strong> Strong Asia-Pacific and Gulf presence. India coverage often included.</li>
    <li><strong>Allianz Care:</strong> Good global coverage at competitive prices.</li>
    <li><strong>ICICI Lombard:</strong> Indian insurer with some international products. Familiar brand, includes India coverage.</li>
  </ul>

  <CTABox
    title="US Healthcare Costs"
    description="If you're moving to the United States, healthcare costs are extreme. A single hospital stay can cost $50,000-$200,000+. Comprehensive insurance isn't optional—it's essential for financial protection."
    buttonText="Get US Coverage Quote"
    buttonHref="/go/cigna-global"
    variant="highlight"
  />

  <h2 id="leaving-india">Leaving Indian Healthcare</h2>
  <p>
    India has a mixed public-private healthcare system. Here's what happens when you leave:
  </p>

  <h3>ESIC (Employee State Insurance)</h3>
  <p>
    If you're covered under ESIC through your employer, this coverage ends when you leave Indian employment. ESIC is tied to specific employers and provides no international coverage.
  </p>

  <h3>CGHS (Central Government Health Scheme)</h3>
  <p>
    Government employees have CGHS coverage. This only works in India—there's no international extension. Government employees abroad need separate international insurance.
  </p>

  <h3>Private Indian Insurance</h3>
  <p>
    Private health insurance from Indian companies (Star Health, ICICI Lombard, HDFC Ergo) typically provides limited international coverage—usually 30-90 days of emergency treatment abroad. For long-term stays overseas, you need dedicated international coverage.
  </p>

  <h3>Ayushman Bharat</h3>
  <p>
    The government's health insurance scheme covers eligible families but only within India. It provides no international coverage whatsoever.
  </p>

  <h2 id="destination-considerations">Destination Considerations</h2>
  <p>
    Indian expats face different challenges depending on destination:
  </p>

  <h3>Gulf Countries (UAE, Saudi, Qatar, Kuwait)</h3>
  <p>
    Many Gulf countries require employer-provided health insurance. However, employer plans often have limitations—coverage may end if you lose your job, and family coverage may be inadequate. Supplemental international insurance provides security.
  </p>

  <h3>United States</h3>
  <p>
    US healthcare is the most expensive globally. H-1B workers typically have employer coverage, but it ends with employment. International insurance provides continuity and often costs less than COBRA continuation coverage.
  </p>

  <h3>United Kingdom</h3>
  <p>
    NHS provides free healthcare to legal residents with proper visa status. Many Indian expats supplement NHS with private insurance for faster access to specialists and private hospitals.
  </p>

  <h3>Canada and Australia</h3>
  <p>
    Both have public healthcare systems for residents. Waiting periods apply (typically 3 months). International insurance covers the gap and provides options beyond public healthcare.
  </p>

  <div class="bg-amber-50 border border-amber-200 rounded-lg p-6 my-6">
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-amber-900 mb-2">Family Considerations</h3>
    <p class="text-amber-800">
      Indian expats often support extended families. International insurance typically covers spouse and dependent children. Parents visiting from India need separate travel insurance—they won't be covered under your policy.
    </p>
  </div>

  <h2 id="comparison-table">Quick Comparison</h2>
  <ComparisonTable columns={comparisonColumns} rows={comparisonRows} />

  <h2 id="detailed-reviews">Detailed Reviews</h2>

  <h3>Cigna Global</h3>
  <p>
    Cigna Global offers comprehensive international coverage ideal for Indian expats. Strong networks in the US (critical for H-1B workers) and Gulf countries (large Indian populations). Plans come in three tiers with coverage up to unlimited.
  </p>

  <p>
    24/7 English service, direct billing at major hospitals worldwide. India coverage can be added for visits home.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Best for:</strong> Indian expats who want reliable global coverage, especially in the US or Gulf.
  </p>

  <h3>Bupa Global</h3>
  <p>
    Bupa Global offers premium international coverage with excellent worldwide networks. Service quality is outstanding—fast claims, helpful support, comprehensive benefits including mental health and maternity.
  </p>

  <p>
    Higher pricing reflects premium quality. Best for professionals who can afford top-tier coverage.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Best for:</strong> Indian professionals who want the best coverage available.
  </p>

  <h3>Now Health</h3>
  <p>
    Now Health has strong presence in Asia-Pacific and the Gulf—regions with large Indian expat populations. India coverage is often included automatically. Good option for those in Singapore, Hong Kong, or UAE.
  </p>

  <p>
    Service is good, pricing is competitive for Asian coverage.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Best for:</strong> Indian expats in Asia-Pacific or Gulf who want included India coverage.
  </p>

  <h3>Allianz Care</h3>
  <p>
    Allianz Care offers good global coverage at competitive prices. Strong networks in Europe and adequate coverage elsewhere. Good option for Indian expats in European destinations.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Best for:</strong> Indian expats seeking good value, especially for European destinations.
  </p>

  <h3>ICICI Lombard</h3>
  <p>
    ICICI Lombard is one of India's largest private insurers and offers some international products. Familiar brand, familiar processes, India coverage included. International networks are more limited than dedicated international insurers.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Best for:</strong> Indian expats who prefer familiar Indian service and primarily need India coverage.
  </p>

  <CTABox
    title="Compare Your Options"
    description="Get quotes from multiple providers to find the best balance of network strength, coverage, and price for your destination."
    buttonText="Get Free Quotes"
    buttonHref="/go/cigna-global"
  />

  <h2 id="popular-destinations">Popular Destinations</h2>
  <p>
    Insurance needs vary by destination. Here's what Indian expats should consider:
  </p>

  <h3>United States</h3>
  <p>
    Largest Indian expat population outside India. H-1B workers need to understand employer coverage limitations. Tech hubs (Bay Area, Seattle, Austin) have excellent hospitals but extreme costs. Comprehensive coverage is essential.
  </p>

  <h3>United Arab Emirates</h3>
  <p>
    Dubai and Abu Dhabi have large Indian communities. Health insurance is mandatory—employers must provide it. Supplemental coverage ensures continuity and better benefits. Many Indian doctors practice in the UAE.
  </p>

  <h3>United Kingdom</h3>
  <p>
    NHS covers legal residents. Large Indian communities in London, Birmingham, Leicester. Private insurance provides faster access. Many NHS doctors are of Indian origin.
  </p>

  <h3>Canada</h3>
  <p>
    Provincial healthcare after 3-month waiting period. Toronto, Vancouver, and Calgary have significant Indian populations. International insurance covers the waiting period and provides supplementary coverage.
  </p>

  <h3>Saudi Arabia</h3>
  <p>
    Large Indian workforce. Employer-provided insurance is mandatory. Coverage quality varies—international insurance can supplement basic employer plans.
  </p>

  <h2 id="faqs">Common Questions</h2>

  <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">Does Indian insurance cover me abroad?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">Most Indian policies provide limited international coverage (30-90 days emergency only). For long-term stays abroad, you need dedicated international health insurance.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">What if my US employer provides insurance?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">Employer insurance ends with employment. H-1B workers face gaps during job transitions. International insurance provides continuity and often costs less than COBRA.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">Is Gulf employer insurance enough?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">Gulf employer plans vary in quality. Some are comprehensive; others have significant limitations. Review your employer plan carefully and consider supplemental coverage.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">What about coverage during India visits?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">Most international insurers offer India as a coverage region. ICICI Lombard and Now Health include it automatically. Confirm details with your chosen provider.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">Can I cover my parents in India?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">International expat policies typically cover spouse and dependent children only. Parents need separate coverage—consider Indian domestic health insurance for them.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">Are there Indian doctors abroad?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">Yes, especially in the UK, US, Gulf, and other countries with large Indian populations. Your insurer covers any qualified doctor, and Indian community networks can help find familiar providers.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2>Final Verdict</h2>
  <p>
    Indian expats need comprehensive international insurance—Indian coverage doesn't extend abroad meaningfully. <strong>Cigna Global</strong> is our top recommendation for reliable coverage in the US and Gulf. <strong>Bupa Global</strong> offers premium coverage for those who want the best.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Now Health</strong> suits those in Asia-Pacific or Gulf who want included India coverage. <strong>Allianz Care</strong> provides good value for European destinations. <strong>ICICI Lombard</strong> works for those who prefer familiar Indian service.
  </p>

  <p>
    Don't rely solely on employer coverage—it ends with employment. International insurance provides continuity and security regardless of job changes.
  </p>

</PageShell>
